681
00:37:32.592 --> 00:37:36.531
2026 because it quietly shifts control

682
00:37:36.592 --> 00:37:39.732
of a public resource away from the public.

683
00:37:40.632 --> 00:37:44.352
The submitters, or the majority of the submitters I would say, representing

684
00:37:44.412 --> 00:37:47.892
tens of thousands of New Zealanders, reject the bill entirely.

685
00:37:47.982 --> 00:37:51.902
Not because the fisheries don't need improvement, but because this

686
00:37:52.032 --> 00:37:54.252
bill doesn't fix the real problem.

687
00:37:55.132 --> 00:37:57.112
The current law is already strong.

688
00:37:57.422 --> 00:37:59.952
The failure has been in how it's applied.

689
00:38:00.472 --> 00:38:03.972
And instead of improving implementation, this bill

690
00:38:04.012 --> 00:38:07.612
rewrites the rules, so past failures become

691
00:38:07.622 --> 00:38:11.172
acceptable. Now here's the important part.

692
00:38:11.692 --> 00:38:15.392
You can't understand this bill by looking at one clause at a time.

693
00:38:15.412 --> 00:38:16.272
And in fact, Miles, you

694
00:38:16.732 --> 00:38:20.422
spoke to some earlier

695
00:38:20.612 --> 00:38:24.532
submitters and asked them, "What aspect of the bill do you not like?"

696
00:38:24.612 --> 00:38:28.272
It's the whole thing, because the changes seem technical, but they form a

697
00:38:28.332 --> 00:38:31.972
pattern. Environmental protections are narrowed, public

698
00:38:32.052 --> 00:38:35.812
input is reduced, accountability is weakened, and

699
00:38:35.932 --> 00:38:39.872
legal challenge becomes harder. Taken together, this is

700
00:38:39.892 --> 00:38:43.412
what's known as regulatory capture, where the industry being

701
00:38:43.472 --> 00:38:46.872
regulated gains influence over the rules themselves.

702
00:38:47.832 --> 00:38:50.652
Okay? Take a look at what gets overlooked.

703
00:38:50.662 --> 00:38:54.472
The bill limits how environmental factors are considered when setting catch

704
00:38:54.532 --> 00:38:58.452
limits. It focuses on large management areas, which can

705
00:38:58.492 --> 00:39:02.372
hide local depletion. So while numbers may look stable on paper,

706
00:39:03.012 --> 00:39:06.272
entire local ecosystems can be quietly degrading.

707
00:39:06.872 --> 00:39:10.812
Even more concerning, the less we know about a fish stock, the

708
00:39:10.892 --> 00:39:12.712
weaker the legal protection becomes.

709
00:39:13.212 --> 00:39:16.222
That reverses a basic principle of good management.

710
00:39:16.841 --> 00:39:20.192
Uncertainty should lead to caution, not leniency.

711
00:39:21.372 --> 00:39:24.012
The bill also shifts how decisions are made.

712
00:39:24.032 --> 00:39:27.772
It allows reliance on industry catch data as a primary signal.

713
00:39:28.172 --> 00:39:31.952
It introduces preset rules run by officials instead of

714
00:39:32.012 --> 00:39:35.672
ministers, and it leans on voluntary industry measures

715
00:39:36.152 --> 00:39:38.492
instead of enforceable regulation.

716
00:39:39.172 --> 00:39:43.072
On the surface, that sounds efficient, but when you look closer, it

717
00:39:43.112 --> 00:39:47.032
moves decision-making away from independent oversight towards

718
00:39:47.052 --> 00:39:50.712
systems influenced by the very groups that benefit from higher

719
00:39:50.872 --> 00:39:51.612
catch limits.

720
00:39:53.932 --> 00:39:56.992
Then there are the incentives, the quiet drivers of behavior.

721
00:39:57.362 --> 00:40:00.732
The bill allows more discarding of fish at sea.

722
00:40:00.792 --> 00:40:04.312
It enables unused quota to be carried forward in large amounts,

723
00:40:04.952 --> 00:40:06.712
and it reduces certain penalties.

724
00:40:07.232 --> 00:40:11.052
None of these sound dramatic on their own, but together they encourage

725
00:40:11.172 --> 00:40:15.092
overfishing, waste, and delayed response to declining

726
00:40:15.102 --> 00:40:15.612
stocks.

727
00:40:16.812 --> 00:40:18.922
At the same time, transparency is reduced.

728
00:40:19.432 --> 00:40:22.372
Camera footage from fishing vessels can be withheld.

729
00:40:22.412 --> 00:40:26.212
Public consultation is limited, and the timeframe to legally challenge

730
00:40:26.222 --> 00:40:30.092
decisions is cut to just 20 days. So even if something

731
00:40:30.132 --> 00:40:33.692
goes wrong, it becomes much harder to see it, question

732
00:40:33.732 --> 00:40:34.912
it, and stop it.

733
00:40:35.972 --> 00:40:39.052
So step back and a deeper pattern emerges.

734
00:40:39.112 --> 00:40:42.222
When you look at the whole picture, decisions are made earlier,

735
00:40:42.872 --> 00:40:45.292
public input comes later or not at all,

736
00:40:46.332 --> 00:40:48.091
and legal challenge is constrained.

737
00:40:48.612 --> 00:40:52.591
This locks in commercial interests first and limits the abilities

738
00:40:52.672 --> 00:40:53.972
of others to respond.

739
00:40:55.292 --> 00:40:55.532
So

740
00:40:57.392 --> 00:41:00.012
this isn't just a technical fisheries bill.

741
00:41:00.032 --> 00:41:03.632
It's a shift in who holds power over a shared natural

742
00:41:03.672 --> 00:41:07.432
resource. The real question isn't whether this improves

743
00:41:07.492 --> 00:41:11.252
efficiency. The real question is: who

744
00:41:11.352 --> 00:41:13.432
are our fisheries being managed for?

745
00:41:13.972 --> 00:41:17.832
Because when you look closely, the biggest change here isn't in the

746
00:41:17.892 --> 00:41:18.772
wording of the law,

747
00:41:19.672 --> 00:41:22.072
it's in who the system ultimately serves.

748
00:41:22.932 --> 00:41:26.492
It moves decision-making away from independent oversight

749
00:41:26.552 --> 00:41:30.512
towards systems influenced by the very groups that benefit from higher

750
00:41:30.652 --> 00:41:31.352
catch limits.

751
00:41:32.172 --> 00:41:34.892
This bill should be rejected outright.

752
00:41:36.112 --> 00:41:40.092
Good government is about regulating excessive imbalance of power in

753
00:41:40.132 --> 00:41:44.042
society. I think it is entirely legitimate that owners of

754
00:41:44.052 --> 00:41:48.012
fishing quota are regulated to ensure the methods they use only catch

755
00:41:48.052 --> 00:41:52.032
the fish they are entitled to in the amounts they are entitled

756
00:41:52.052 --> 00:41:55.892
to without killing many other species and damaging the marine

757
00:41:55.932 --> 00:41:56.512
habitats.

758
00:41:57.412 --> 00:42:01.202
Does owning fish quota allow you to wreck the place and

759
00:42:01.252 --> 00:42:05.132
kill indiscriminately? This bill is designed to allow

760
00:42:05.432 --> 00:42:08.552
and encourage commercial interests to do just that.

